4. Medauroidea extradentata
5. Deroplatys lobata
6. Phyllium giganteum
Which one is your favorite?

node.text:
Yoga and Meditation with Guru Turtle 🧘🏼‍♂️Share your photos with us and we will post them in our account. Apply for a feature following the link in our bio: @explorerfervor 

This unique type of meditation is all about relaxation and being one with the ocean 🌿😄

The Great Barrier Reef in the Australian estate of Queensland is home to six out of seven of the world's sea turtle species. Not only this coast is radiant with sunshine, but its picturesque landscapes are also overflowing with an impressive population of native animals.

From witnessing baby turtles make their way to the sea to see adult turtles enjoying @nature, that's a magical sight to behold.

Tag your @nature lovers friends! 🐢

📽 @jacintashackleton
📍 Queensland, Australia
🎶 Arnaud Gauthier - Yoga

Made up from 18 rocky, rugged islands, it offers a spot for endless adventures, whether you prefer hiking through green valleys, discovering fjords or admiring the views from coastal cliffs. node.text:
Giant humpback whale 🐋Apply for a feature following the link in our bio and we will publish your content in our account: @explorerfervor 

"Encounters like this don’t happen very often on the ocean. The only way something as magical as this can occur is if the animal engages with you first. Encounters like this cannot be forced but when they do occur, we promise they’re life changing! There is nothing like having a 30 ton animal lock eyes with you."

The humpback whale (Megaptera novaeangliae) is a species of baleen whale. It is one of the larger rorqual species, with adults ranging in length from 12–16 m (39–52 ft) and weighing around 25–30 t (28–33 short tons). The humpback has a distinctive body shape, with long pectoral fins and a knobbly head. It is known for breaching and other distinctive surface behaviors, making it popular with whale watchers. They can live up to 100 years and they are omnivores, their diet is mostly krill, plankton and small fish.

The longest migration undergone by any mammal species is that of the humpback whale (Megaptera novaeangliae), which migrates up to 8200 km each way.

Males produce a complex song lasting 10 to 20 minutes, which they repeat for hours at a time. All the males in a group will produce the same song, which is different each season.

📽 @captainbeezer via @condorexpresssb
📍Santa Bárbara, California
